# Tailwind CSS & Color Variables Rules

## Core Principle
**ALWAYS prefer CSS variables over hardcoded colors.** This ensures consistency, maintainability, and proper dark mode support.

## Available CSS Variables

### Semantic Colors (Use These First)
These are defined in `app/app.css` and automatically switch for dark mode:

| Variable | Usage | Tailwind Class |
|----------|-------|----------------|
| `--background` | Page backgrounds | `bg-background` |
| `--foreground` | Primary text | `text-foreground` |
| `--card` | Card backgrounds | `bg-card` |
| `--card-foreground` | Card text | `text-card-foreground` |
| `--primary` | Primary buttons, links | `bg-primary`, `text-primary` |
| `--primary-foreground` | Text on primary | `text-primary-foreground` |
| `--secondary` | Secondary actions | `bg-secondary`, `text-secondary` |
| `--secondary-foreground` | Text on secondary | `text-secondary-foreground` |
| `--muted` | Muted backgrounds | `bg-muted` |
| `--muted-foreground` | Muted text | `text-muted-foreground` |
| `--accent` | Accent highlights | `bg-accent`, `text-accent` |
| `--accent-foreground` | Text on accent | `text-accent-foreground` |
| `--destructive` | Error/danger states | `bg-destructive`, `text-destructive` |
| `--border` | Borders | `border-border` |
| `--input` | Input backgrounds | `bg-input` |
| `--ring` | Focus rings | `ring-ring` |

### Text Hierarchy Variables
| Variable | Usage | Tailwind Class |
|----------|-------|----------------|
| `--text-heading` | Headings, titles | `text-text-heading` |
| `--text-body` | Body text | `text-text-body` |
| `--text-body-subtle` | Secondary text | `text-text-body-subtle` |

### Brand Colors (Full Palette)
For brand-specific styling, use the brand scale:
- `bg-brand-50` through `bg-brand-950`
- `text-brand-50` through `text-brand-950`
- `border-brand-50` through `border-brand-950`

### Sidebar Variables
For sidebar-specific styling:
- `--sidebar`, `--sidebar-foreground`
- `--sidebar-primary`, `--sidebar-primary-foreground`
- `--sidebar-accent`, `--sidebar-accent-foreground`
- `--sidebar-border`, `--sidebar-ring`

### Chart Colors
For data visualization:
- `--chart-1` through `--chart-5`

## Decision Flow

### When Styling a Component:

1. **First, check if a semantic variable exists:**
   ```tsx
   // ✅ CORRECT - Uses semantic variable
   <div className="bg-background text-foreground">
   
   // ❌ WRONG - Hardcoded color
   <div className="bg-[#F9FAFB] text-[#1a1a1a]">
   ```

2. **If no semantic variable fits, check if a brand color works:**
   ```tsx
   // ✅ CORRECT - Uses brand palette
   <div className="bg-brand-100 text-brand-900">
   
   // ❌ WRONG - Arbitrary color
   <div className="bg-[#e0e7ff]">
   ```

3. **If a new color is truly needed, ADD IT TO `app/app.css` first:**
   ```css
   /* In :root section of app/app.css */
   --success: oklch(0.72 0.19 142.5);
   --success-foreground: oklch(1.0 0 0);
   ```
   
   Then register it in the `@theme inline` block:
   ```css
   @theme inline {
     --color-success: var(--success);
     --color-success-foreground: var(--success-foreground);
   }
   ```
   
   Then use it:
   ```tsx
   <div className="bg-success text-success-foreground">
   ```

4. **For dark mode support, also add to `.dark` section:**
   ```css
   .dark {
     --success: oklch(0.65 0.17 140.2);
     --success-foreground: oklch(1.0 0 0);
   }
   ```

## Forbidden Patterns

### ❌ Never Use Hardcoded Colors in Classes
```tsx
// BAD - Hardcoded hex
<div className="bg-[#003362]">

// BAD - Hardcoded rgb
<div className="text-[rgb(100,100,100)]">

// BAD - Hardcoded oklch in className
<div className="bg-[oklch(0.5_0.1_250)]">
```

### ❌ Never Use Tailwind's Default Palette for Semantic UI
```tsx
// BAD - Using Tailwind defaults instead of semantic vars
<button className="bg-blue-600 text-white">

// GOOD - Using semantic vars
<button className="bg-primary text-primary-foreground">
```

### ✅ Exception: Tailwind Grays for Layout
Using Tailwind's gray scale is acceptable for subtle layout purposes:
```tsx
// OK - Using gray for subtle borders/dividers
<div className="border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800">
```

## Quick Reference: Common Replacements

| Instead of... | Use... |
|---------------|--------|
| `bg-white` | `bg-background` or `bg-card` |
| `text-gray-900` | `text-foreground` or `text-text-heading` |
| `text-gray-600` | `text-muted-foreground` or `text-text-body` |
| `text-gray-400` | `text-text-body-subtle` |
| `bg-blue-600` | `bg-primary` |
| `bg-blue-100` | `bg-brand-100` |
| `border-gray-200` | `border-border` |
| `bg-gray-100` | `bg-muted` |
| `bg-red-500` | `bg-destructive` |

## Adding New CSS Variables

When you need a color that doesn't exist:

1. **Name it semantically** (by purpose, not by color):
   - ✅ `--success`, `--warning`, `--info`
   - ❌ `--green`, `--yellow`, `--blue-light`

2. **Use OKLCH color format** for consistency with existing variables:
   ```css
   --success: oklch(0.72 0.19 142.5);
   ```

3. **Always define both light and dark variants** in their respective sections

4. **Register in `@theme inline`** to make it available as a Tailwind class

## File Reference
- **CSS Variables Location:** `app/app.css`
- **Light mode variables:** `:root { ... }`
- **Dark mode variables:** `.dark { ... }`
- **Tailwind theme mapping:** `@theme inline { ... }`
